# .gitattributes — line-ending and binary policy
#
# Default: auto-detect text files and let git normalize them on
# commit (using the committer's local convention) and rewrite on
# checkout to the repository convention. Explicit per-extension
# rules below override this default for files where the convention
# matters or where the content is binary.
#
# Applied policy: existing files in the repo are NOT mass-renormalized
# when this file is introduced (`git add --renormalize .` is not run).
# Only commits made after this file lands respect the rules. A future
# cleanup PR can renormalize if desired — kept separate so the diff
# doesn't pollute blame.

* text=auto

# === Windows-native scripting / tooling: CRLF ===
# AHK itself accepts both line endings, but the project's historical
# editing tools (Notepad++, the AHK error dialog) work better with
# CRLF, and the build / tray flows are Windows-only.
*.ahk text eol=crlf
*.ps1 text eol=crlf
*.bat text eol=crlf
*.cmd text eol=crlf

# === Docs and structured config: LF ===
# Cross-platform default; GitHub renders both, but LF avoids spurious
# diffs when a contributor edits on macOS/Linux.
*.md   text eol=lf
*.csv  text eol=lf
*.yml  text eol=lf
*.yaml text eol=lf
*.json text eol=lf

# === INI: treat as binary ===
# AHK's IniWrite produces UTF-16 LE with a BOM and CRLF line
# endings. If git ever tried to text-normalize one of these files
# the BOM would be clobbered and the next IniRead would return
# empty. None of the project's INIs are committed today (all listed
# in .gitignore), but the rule is a guardrail for any future
# addition (templates, fixtures, etc.).
*.ini binary

# === Images and archives: binary ===
*.png  binary
*.jpg  binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif  binary
*.ico  binary
*.zip  binary
*.exe  binary
